	<td class="alt1">
	
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				
				<strong>I spent a while posting on this exact topic...</strong>
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>in the various threads on SoE's board posted by the people who think since there's 16 classes clerics should only be required in the 1/16 ratio or something around 3 clerics per 54 man raid.<br />
<br />
There's a couple of base problems, one is they keep adding classes, but notice no new priest classes.  Adding more DPS classes just causes people to whine even more about the ratio of clerics to other classes on raids.<br />
<br />
Lowering the healing required so that 3 clerics, 3 druids, and 3 shaman could heal a 54 man raid would (with current healing abilities) make the raids entirely gimp for 6 clerics 2 druids and 2 shaman. There isn't any two ways about it.  About the only thing you could try at that point would be to set mob regen so high that the DPS required forced you to have max geared melee/nukers as say 49 people in your raid, and that's an even harder line to try juggling than the healing because there is a pretty good variation in melee dps from a lot of different reasons.  It'd be funny though if the raid changed from todays melees can mostly afk okay, but afk'ing as a healer could wipe a raide to being a healer thats afk was mostly okay but being a melee and going afk could lose the fight because that last little bit of dps was needed to get over the mobs regen.<br />
<br />
People do min/max raid mix's period.  This will continue to happen unless some limiit to the number of x class per instanced raid is instituted.  This would really hurt most end game guilds badly though because their classes aren't balanced as it is.  They have lots of clerics, warriors, rogues, and wizards relative to other classes (with clerics and warriors being the most prevalent in most guilds.)<br />
<br />
If OoW raiding is more like PoP raiding then giving dru/shm a "raid ch" would make a difference.  Honestly I don't think giving them a raid ch would have changed much in GoD (so that's somewhat content dependent.)  There are ways to give them a heal without making it only work in raids or via a buff without breaking the current group balancing.  How about AE heals (direct for druids and HoT's for shaman.)  Make them generate low aggro, and be small heal/large mana.  Druid Raid_Heal_1 level: 65 mana:900 heals 300ae almost zero aggro.  Now one druid won't really do that much with it, (and he'd never use it in a grind group) but 4 druids casting that together could heal quite alot of ramp/ae/etc damage.<br />
<br />
Anyway, people will always adjust groups to give themselves the maximum shot at winning period.  This means that unless healing parity is achieved between the priests that clerics will continue to be massively overrepresented on raids as long as it's possible for guilds to keep them in those ratios.  Obviously that kind of healing parity has some real issues in the current raid game, much less the 6man/grind game.  If druids and shaman had healing parity because of the other roles they coudl take on raids the number of clerics would probably be reduced to the minimum needed to be able to rez during fights and not much else.<br />
<br />
I personally don't think you can change this stuff without just breaking to much things in the game unless you really come up with a different way to add raid healing to shaman and druids.  The AE heals would work, there is probably other ways to do that as well.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
